=E2=80=9CI Love It! I=E2=80=99ll Take
It!=E2=80=9D
-------------------------

A Bulgarian-born Armenian, Tavitian escaped the Iron Curtain with his famil=
y at the age
of 19, and in 1961 arrived in New York, where he worked as a taxi driver an=
d, in short order, scored a scholarship to study nuclear engineering at Col=
umbia. From there, he and some fellow students founded the software company=
 Syncsort, the major sort program for the IBM mainframe during its heyday. =
Tavitian later bought out his partners and served as C.E.O. from 1975 to 20=
08, before selling a large portion of the company. The estate=E2=80=99s sha=
re of the proceeds from Sotheby=E2=80=99s sales will benefit his
foundation, which he founded in 1995 to support development in the Armenian=
 region, scholarships for students of Armenian origin, and, of course, the =
arts.

=C2=A0

Tavitian began collecting seriously only in the early 2000s, knowing almost=
 nothing, and it=E2=80=99s remarkable what he accomplished in such a short =
time. He was passionate, loved the thrill of the chase, and was determined =
to own something once he decided he
wanted it. =E2=80=9CI love it! I=E2=80=99ll take it!=E2=80=9D dealer Alexis=
 Kugel recalled him saying, adding: =E2=80=9CAso Tavitian was one of the mo=
st intuitive and enthusiastic collectors I ever met.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Nobody knows why or how Tavitian first became interested in the English fur=
niture that comprises the bulk of his collection, but from the beginning, h=
e worked closely with furniture restorer Peter Holmes, sending
all the items he purchased straight to Holmes=E2=80=99s workshop in London.=
 He never bought something without knowing exactly where he was going to pl=
ace it.=C2=A0

