x;">A Bulgarian-born Armenian, Tavitian escaped the Iron Curtain with his f=
amily at the age
of 19, and in 1961 arrived in New York, where he worked as a taxi driver an=
d, in short order, scored a scholarship to study nuclear engineering at Col=
umbia. From there, he and some fellow students founded the software company=
 Syncsort, the major sort program for the IBM mainframe during its heyday. =
Tavitian later bought out his partners and served as C.E.O. from 1975 to 20=
08, before selling a large portion of the company. The estate=E2=80=99s sha=
re of the proceeds from Sotheby=E2=80=99s sales will benefit his
foundation, which he founded in 1995 to support development in the Armenian=
 region, scholarships for students of Armenian origin, and, of course, the =
arts.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Tavitian began collecting seriously only in the e=
arly 2000s, knowing almost nothing, and it=E2=80=99s remarkable what he acc=
omplished in such a short time. He was passionate, loved the thrill of the =
chase, and was determined to own something once he decided he
wanted it. =E2=80=9C<em>I love it! I=E2=80=99ll take it!</em>=E2=80=9D deal=
er <strong>Alexis Kugel</strong> recalled him saying, adding: =E2=80=9CAso =
Tavitian was one of the most intuitive and enthusiastic collectors I ever m=
et.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;">Nobody knows why or how Tavitian first became interested in =
the English furniture that comprises the bulk of his collection, but from t=
he beginning, he worked closely with furniture restorer <strong>Peter Holme=
s</strong>, sending
all the items he purchased straight to Holmes=E2=80=99s workshop in London.=
 He never bought something without knowing exactly where he was going to pl=
ace it.=C2=A0</p></div>
